    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm running a linear regression on some housing price data but my residual plots are looking pretty messy. The residuals don't look normally distributed at all, and I'm seeing some pretty heavy skewness. What's the best way to handle this to fix the violation of the normality assumption?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Messy residual plots, especially with heavy skewness, can be a real headache for your linear regression, but don't let it scare you! You can try a few things to handle this violation of the normality assumption. First, you could try transforming your dependent variable or your residuals themselves to see if that smooths things out.\n\nIf the skewness is severe, a log transformation on the housing prices might be a good first step. You can also try a Box-Cox transformation, which is a more flexible method that finds the optimal power transformation to make the data more normal. Sometimes, just taking the natural logarithm of the residuals will make them behave better, which is what you'd want if you were trying to make a proper, well-behaved model.",
      "source": "target",
