    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i tried the log transformation but the skewness is still pretty bad in some parts of the distribution. it feels like there are these huge outliers pulling everything out of whack. do you think i should just drop those rows, or is there a more formal way to deal with outliers that are causing this lack of normality?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Dropping rows is a blunt instrument, and you should generally try to avoid it unless you have a very clear, justifiable reason, like a data entry error. A more formal approach is usually better, like using robust regression techniques or Winsorizing the data.\n\nWinsorizing involves capping the extreme values—setting them to a certain percentile value instead of deleting them entirely. This keeps your data points but limits the influence of those massive outliers, which can help your residuals look much more symmetrical. You could also explore using a robust regression method, like M-estimation, which is less sensitive to outliers than standard Ordinary Least Squares (OLS).",
      "source": "target",
