    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay, so if i went with the robust regression route, how would that actually change the way the model treats those extreme points? like, what is it doing mathematically differently than OLS to stop the outliers from messing up the fit?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Robust regression, unlike OLS, is less concerned with minimizing the squared errors of every single point. OLS, being the standard, is very sensitive to outliers because those large errors get squared, meaning a single massive outlier can drag the entire regression line way off course.\n\nRobust methods, however, use a different loss function. Instead of squaring the residuals (which gives huge weight to outliers), they use a function that grows less rapidly as the residuals get bigger. For instance, methods like Huber loss or Tukey's biweight function down-weight those extreme residuals. Essentially, they treat those outliers as less important, giving them less mathematical \"pull\" on the final line.",
      "source": "target",
